hormone-related protein and Interleukin 6"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECancer cachexia is a syndrome characterised by severe weight loss, muscle wasting, and systemic inflammation. It is commonly associated with advanced cancer and significantly impacts patient quality of life and survival. \u003Cstrong\u003ETumour necrosis factor alpha and Interleukin 6\u003C/strong\u003E are key cytokines that contribute to skeletal muscle atrophy in cancer cachexia. These cytokines promote muscle protein breakdown and inhibit muscle protein synthesis, leading to muscle wasting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterleukin 1 and Interleukin 6\u003C/strong\u003E - While IL-6 is involved, IL-1 is not a primary cytokine in muscle atrophy in cachexia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParathyroid hormone-related protein and Interleukin 1\u003C/strong\u003E - These are not the main cytokines involved in muscle atrophy in cachexia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETumour necrosis factor alpha and Interleukin 1\u003C/strong\u003E - TNF\u03b1 is involved, but IL-1 is not a primary cytokine in this context\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParathyroid hormone-related protein and Interleukin 6\u003C/strong\u003E - Parathyroid hormone-related protein is not primarily involved in muscle atrophy in cachexia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tumour necrosis factor alpha (TNF\u03b1) and interleukin 6 (IL-6) are key cytokines involved in skeletal muscle atrophy in cancer cachexia.","Cancer cachexia is a complex syndrome characterised by weight loss, muscle wasting, and systemic inflammation.","Cytokines like TNF\u03b1 and IL-6 promote muscle protein breakdown and inhibit muscle protein synthesis."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Longo, U. G., \u0026 Denaro, V. (Eds.). (2023). Textbook of musculoskeletal disorders. Springer Nature","Hughes, S. H. (2022). The Musculoskeletal System: The Musculoskeletal System-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Frontera WR, Ochala J. Skeletal muscle: a brief review of structure and function. Calcif Tissue Int. 2015 Mar;96(3):183-95. doi: 10.1007/s00223-014-9915-y. Epub 2014 Oct 8. PMID: 25294644","Morrison BM. Neuromuscular Diseases. Semin Neurol. 2016 Oct;36(5):409-418. doi: 10.1055/s-0036-1586263. Epub 2016 Sep 23. PMID: 27704495","Suzuki H, Asakawa A, Amitani H, Nakamura N, Inui A. Cancer cachexia--pathophysiology and management. J Gastroenterol. 2013 May;48(5):574-94. doi: 10.1007/s00535-013-0787-0. Epub 2013 Mar 20. PMID: 23512346; PMCID: PMC3698426."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60015"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18414"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60015"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T06:05:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T06:06:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11132"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74524"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co